Pure pashmina products are made from the downy undercoat fibers collected from a special breed of goat during molting season. The best pashminas however, come from the Changthang Plateau in Kashmir, where conditions are optimal for the goats to produce their super-soft undercoat.

Because of the extremely fine fiber (a mere 12-15 microns) that is used to make 100% pure pashmina products, the end result is an extraordinarily soft and luxurious product. This is because of the unique nature of the pashmina fiber itself.

Pure pashmina products are highly valued and prized because of their quality and the limited supply of the raw material. The process of collecting the pashmina fiber is labor intensive, and yields only a small amount per goat each season, so prices tend to remain high for the pure pashmina products.
